There&#39;s probably a better answer, but since it&#39;s dynamic, TypeScript ofc has no way of knowing what property you&#39;re setting in the for loop.

There&#39;s ways to get around this, such as using `Object.defineProperty()`,  but I normally opt for something like this:

      for (var fld in params) {
          this.board = {[fld]: fld} as any
      }

EDIT:

You can also declare all the properties besides `[prop:string]` as optional (but I assume this is there simply to try to get it to work?). eg:

```
board: {
      [prop:string]: string | string[] | BoardLoadingType | BoardErrorType;
      created_on?: string;
      name?: string;
      threads?: string[];
      updated_on?: string;
      _id?: string;
      delete_password?: string;
      loading?: BoardLoadingType;
      error?: BoardErrorType;
    };
```

The reason for the error is that you&#39;re telling typescript that those properties are absolutely required, and yet you&#39;re instantiating the object without them using the for loop. 

Hope this helps, interested to see other answers :)

First of all, if params may or may not contain certain properties, board has to have optional properties. That can easily be done using the `Partial` generic type:

     board: Partial&lt;{
      [prop:string]: string | string[] | BoardLoadingType | BoardErrorType;
      created_on: string;
      name: string;
      threads: string[];
      updated_on: string;
      _id: string;
      delete_password: string;
      loading: BoardLoadingType;
      error: BoardErrorType;
    }&gt;;

Now if your intention was to copy `params` to `this.board`, that&#39;s easy:

     // Initialize `this.board` once:
     this.board = {};
     // Then fill it with params or whatever
     Object.assign(this.board, params);

You&#39;ll notice that `id` and `_id` do missmatch ... 

----

As a sidenote, your code:

    for (var fld in params) {
     this.board = {[fld]: fld}
    }

Just doesn&#39;t work at all. It&#39;ll reset `this.board` at every iteration to a new object, and that object will have keys as values, e.g. if `params` would be `{ name: &quot;test&quot;, deleted_password: &quot;secret&quot; }`, then `this.board` would result in `{ deleted_password: &quot;deleted_password&quot; }`. Thats probably not what you wanted, and Typescript tried to prevent that for a reason ...

